\f1\b Description:\

\f2\b0 The 
\f0 \cf4 /home
\f2 \cf2  directory is used to support disk storage needs of local users.\

\f1\b Rationale:\

\f2\b0 The default installation only creates a single 
\f0 \cf4 /
\f2 \cf2  partition. Since the 
\f0 \cf4 /home
\f2 \cf2  directory\
contains user generated data, there is a risk of resource exhaustion. It will essentially\
have the whole disk available to fill up and impact the system as a whole. In addition,\
other operations on the system could fill up the disk unrelated to 
\f0 \cf4 /home
\f2 \cf2  and impact all\
local users.\
Configuring 
\f0 \cf4 /home
\f2 \cf2  as its own file system allows an administrator to set additional mount\
options such as 
\f0 \cf4 noexec/nosuid/nodev
\f2 \cf2 . These options limit an attacker's ability to\
create exploits on the system. In the case of 
\f0 \cf4 /home
\f2 \cf2  options such as\

\f0 \cf4 usrquota/grpquota
\f2 \cf2  may be considered to limit the impact that users can have on each\
other with regards to disk resource exhaustion. Other options allow for specific\
behavior. See 
\f0 \cf4 man mount
\f2 \cf2  for exact details regarding filesystem-independent and\
filesystem-specific options.\
As 
\f0 \cf4 /home
\f2 \cf2  contains user data, care should be taken to ensure the security and integrity\
of the data and mount point.\

\f1\b Impact:\

\f2\b0 Resizing filesystems is a common activity in cloud-hosted servers. Separate filesystem\
partitions may prevent successful resizing or may require the installation of additional\
tools solely for the purpose of resizing operations. The use of these additional tools may\
introduce their own security considerations.\

\f1\b Audit:\

\f2\b0 Run the following command and verify output shows 
\f0 \cf4 /home
\f2 \cf2  is mounted:\

\f4\fs20\fsmilli10080 # findmnt -kn /home\
