\f1\b Description:\

\f2\b0 SELinux can run in one of three modes: disabled, permissive, or enforcing:\

\f0\fs20\fsmilli10080 \'95
\f2  
\f0\fs24 \cf4 Enforcing
\f2 \cf2  - Is the default, and recommended, mode of operation; in enforcing\
mode SELinux operates normally, enforcing the loaded security policy on the\
entire system.\

\f0\fs20\fsmilli10080 \'95
\f2  
\f0\fs24 \cf4 Permissive
\f2 \cf2  - The system acts as if SELinux is enforcing the loaded security\
policy, including labeling objects and emitting access denial entries in the logs,\
but it does not actually deny any operations. While not recommended for\
production systems, permissive mode can be helpful for SELinux policy\
development.\

\f0\fs20\fsmilli10080 \'95
\f2  
\f0\fs24 \cf4 Disabled
\f2 \cf2  - disables most of the SELinux kernel and application code, leaving\
the system running without any SELinux protection.\

\f1\b Note:
\f2\b0  You can set individual domains to permissive mode while the system runs in\
enforcing mode. For example, to make the httpd_t domain permissive:\

\f4\fs20\fsmilli10080 # semanage permissive -a httpd_t\

\f1\b\fs24 Rationale:\

\f2\b0 Running SELinux in disabled mode is strongly discouraged; not only does the system\
avoid enforcing the SELinux policy, it also avoids labeling any persistent objects such\
as files, making it difficult to enable SELinux in the future.
\fs20\fsmilli10080 Page 152\

