\f1\b Description:\

\f0\b0 \cf4 crontab
\f2 \cf2  is the program used to install, deinstall, or list the tables used to drive the cron\
daemon. Each user can have their own crontab, and though files are created, they are\
not intended to be edited directly.\
If the 
\f0 \cf4 /etc/cron.allow
\f2 \cf2  file exists, then you must be listed (one user per line) therein in\
order to be allowed to use this command. If the 
\f0 \cf4 /etc/cron.allow
\f2 \cf2  file does not exist but\
the 
\f0 \cf4 /etc/cron.deny
\f2 \cf2  file does exist, then you must not be listed in the 
\f0 \cf4 /etc/cron.deny\

\f2 \cf2 file in order to use this command.\
If neither of these files exists, then depending on site-dependent configuration\
parameters, only the super user will be allowed to use this command, or all users will be\
able to use this command.\
If both files exist then 
\f0 \cf4 /etc/cron.allow
\f2 \cf2  takes precedence. Which means that\

\f0 \cf4 /etc/cron.deny
\f2 \cf2  is not considered and your user must be listed in 
\f0 \cf4 /etc/cron.allow\

\f2 \cf2 in order to be able to use the crontab.\
Regardless of the existence of any of these files, the root administrative user is always\
allowed to setup a crontab.\
The files 
\f0 \cf4 /etc/cron.allow
\f2 \cf2  and 
\f0 \cf4 /etc/cron.deny
\f2 \cf2 , if they exist, must be either world-\
readable, or readable by group 
\f0 \cf4 crontab
\f2 \cf2 . If they are not, then cron will deny access to\
all users until the permissions are fixed.\
