further specified. Such behavior is defined by setting the target of the zone. There are\
three options - 
\f0 \cf4 ACCEPT
\f2 \cf2 , 
\f0 \cf4 REJECT
\f2 \cf2 , and 
\f0 \cf4 DROP
\f2 \cf2 .\

\f0\fs20\fsmilli10080 \'95
\f2  
\f0\fs24 \cf4 ACCEPT
\f2 \cf2  - you accept all incoming packets except those disabled by a specific\
rule.\

\f0\fs20\fsmilli10080 \'95
\f2  
\f0\fs24 \cf4 REJECT
\f2 \cf2  - you disable all incoming packets except those that you have allowed in\
specific rules and the source machine is informed about the rejection.\

\f0\fs20\fsmilli10080 \'95
\f2  
\f0\fs24 \cf4 DROP
\f2 \cf2  - you disable all incoming packets except those that you have allowed in\
specific rules and no information sent to the source machine.\

\f1\b Note:
\f2\b0  The target may also be set to a fourth option, 
\f0 \cf4 default
\f2 \cf2 . The 
\f0 \cf4 default
\f2 \cf2  target\
provides a convenient way to implement a "deny by default, allow by exception" policy\
within a firewalld zone, while still allowing essential ICMP traffic.\

\f1\b Rationale:\

\f2\b0 To reduce the attack surface of a system, all services and ports should be blocked\
unless required\

